<Layout title="Section 5 – Mobility">
  <h1>Section 5: Mobility</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.5 – Performs Supportive Assistance for Mobility Needs</em></p>
  <p>
    Describe mobility impairment assessment findings, demonstrate nursing interventions for
    impaired mobility, and describe evaluation outcomes.
  </p>

  <h2 id="mobility-assessment">Mobility Impairment Assessment</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Assess muscle strength (Grade 0–5), range of motion, and gait.</li>
    <li>Identify balance disturbances: unsteady gait, orthostatic hypotension, sensory deficits.</li>
    <li>Use standardized fall-risk tools (e.g., Morse Fall Scale, Hendrich II).</li>
    <li>Note assistive devices currently in use (cane, walker, crutches, wheelchair).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="fall-prevention">Fall Prevention</h2>
  <p>Falls are a leading cause of injury in hospitalized patients. Implement individualized prevention strategies.</p>
  <h3>High-Risk Indicators</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Previous fall history, altered mental status, polypharmacy (especially sedatives, antihypertensives, diuretics)</li>
    <li>Orthostatic hypotension, urinary urgency/incontinence, use of ambulatory aids</li>
    <li>Age ≥ 65; decreased lower-extremity strength or proprioception</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Prevention Interventions</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Orient patient to environment; place call light within reach.</li>
    <li>Keep bed in lowest position; lock wheels on bed and wheelchair.</li>
    <li>Ensure non-slip footwear and well-fitting clothing.</li>
    <li>Assist with ambulation and transfers; use gait belt.</li>
    <li>Implement hourly rounding.</li>
    <li>Use bed/chair alarms for high-risk patients.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="body-mechanics">Body Mechanics &amp; Safe Patient Handling</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep back straight; bend at knees and hips when lifting.</li>
    <li>Keep the load close to the body; avoid twisting.</li>
    <li>Use draw sheets, slide boards, and ceiling lifts to reduce injury risk.</li>
    <li>Minimum of two caregivers for dependent patient transfers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="transfer">Transfer Techniques</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Transfer Type</th><th>Key Steps</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Bed to Wheelchair (transfer belt)</td><td>Place wheelchair at 45° angle; lock wheels; instruct patient to push up; pivot and lower slowly</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bed to Stretcher</td><td>Use slide board or draw sheet; align heights; lateral transfer with ≥ 2 staff</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hydraulic Lift</td><td>Required for dependent patients; apply sling correctly; never leave patient unattended in lift</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="ambulation">Ambulation Assistive Devices</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Device</th><th>Indication</th><th>Key Teaching Points</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Cane</td><td>Mild balance/unilateral weakness</td><td>Hold on stronger side; advance cane with weaker leg</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Walker</td><td>Moderate weakness/balance issues</td><td>Advance walker first, then step into it; do not lean forward excessively</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Crutches</td><td>Non-weight-bearing or partial WB</td><td>Support weight on hands, not axillae; teach gait pattern per WB order</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="rom">Range-of-Motion (ROM) Exercises</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Active ROM:</strong> Patient performs independently — maintains strength and flexibility.</li>
    <li><strong>Passive ROM:</strong> Nurse moves the joint — prevents contractures in immobile patients.</li>
    <li><strong>Active-Assistive ROM:</strong> Patient participates with nurse support.</li>
    <li>Move joints gently and slowly through their full range; stop if pain is reported.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Lessons (Sherpath – Chapters 39, 15, 16, 21)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Activity and Movement: Assess and Recognize Cues</li>
    <li>Activity and Movement: Analyze Cues and Prioritize Hypothesis</li>
    <li>Falls; Fall Prevention; Nursing Interventions for Fall Reduction</li>
    <li>Promoting Healthy Aging: Musculoskeletal System</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Readings</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Chapter 39, Immobility: pp. 874–914</li>
    <li>Chapter 15, Clinical Judgment to Reduce Fall Risk and Injuries: pp. 209–225</li>
    <li>Chapter 16, Clinical Judgments to Promote Safe Environments: pp. 226–237</li>
    <li>Chapter 21, Bone and Joint Problems: pp. 290–299</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Clinical Skills</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Assisting with Moving and Positioning a Patient in Bed</li>
    <li>Assisting with the Use of Canes, Walkers, and Crutches</li>
    <li>Transferring from Bed to Wheelchair (Transfer Belt)</li>
    <li>Transferring from Bed to Stretcher</li>
    <li>Performing Range-of-Motion Exercises</li>
    <li>Applying Compression Stockings</li>
    <li>Assisting with Ambulation Using a Gait Belt</li>
    <li>Using a Sequential Compression Device</li>
    <li>Using a Hydraulic Lift</li>
    <li>Care of a Patient with an Immobilization Device / Cast</li>
    <li>Shadow Health Digital Clinical Experience</li>
    <li>SLS Fundamental Scenario 5 – Lisa Rae (Fall and Pressure Ulcer Risk Assessment)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="key-terms">Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Contracture:</strong> Permanent shortening of a muscle or joint — result of prolonged immobility.</li>
    <li><strong>Orthostatic hypotension:</strong> Drop in systolic BP ≥ 20 mmHg when rising; a fall risk factor.</li>
    <li><strong>Gait belt:</strong> Safety belt applied around patient's waist to assist with ambulation and transfers.</li>
    <li><strong>DVT:</strong> Deep vein thrombosis — complication of immobility; prevented by compression stockings, SCDs, early ambulation.</li>
    <li><strong>Sequential Compression Device (SCD):</strong> Pneumatic device applied to legs to prevent DVT.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
